{
  "answer": "In the poem *Resignation*, the speaker makes several specific requests of God, opening with a plea to **\"Guide me, Almighty God, help me, Holy Lord!\"** and continuing with appeals for divine guidance on the soul's path (\"Show me... where it may be best for my soul to mark the Measurer’s will\"), grace and forgiveness for sins (\"Grant me your grace... for my bitter, baleful deeds\"), endurance amid trials (\"Grant me... time and understanding, patience and memory\"), merciful reception despite transgressions (\"receive me nevertheless, Ordainer, for your mercy\"), protection from the devil and evil spirits (\"Let not the Arch-Thief harm me... never let the devil lead me\"), and ultimately transport by angels into eternal joy (\"Let angels... take me into your presence... receive me then... into your glorious joy\").[^1]\n\n[^1]: *Old English Elegies*, ch. 9 (\"Resignation\"), [p-04f5b1](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/09-resignation/translation/#p-04f5b1/).",
